XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
This two vehicle crash occurred just past noon at a four-way, two lane intersection. There is one southbound and one northbound lane. There is one westbound and one eastbound lane that is controlled by a posted stop sign where the two roadways meet. Both roadways are straight, level asphalt with a posted speed limit of 80 kmph (50 mph).
Vehicle one (V1), a 1963 Chevrolet dump truck driven by a 56 year-old male, was traveling eastbound. Vehicle two (V2), a 1990 Ford Ranger 4X2 pick-up driven by a 51 year-old female with one passenger, was traveling southbound. As they approached the intersection V1 disregarded the stop sign and entered the intersection striking the right side of V2. The impact caused V2 to rotate clockwise and travel through the intersection in a southeasterly direction. It departed the roadway and began to travel down an embankment into a field. The vehicle rolled to it's left and came to rest on it's top facing in a southwesterly direction. V1 was able to come to a controlled stop on the south shoulder east of the intersection. V1 was removed from the scene on it's own power. V2 was towed due to damages.
The critical pre-crash event for V1 was coded: this vehicle traveling, crossing over (passing through) intersection. The critical reason for the critical event was attributed to V1 as a driver related factor: false assumption of other actions. The driver stated he thought V2 was going to turn right at the intersection and instead it kept going straight. Physical evidence at the scene indicates V1 did not stop at the stop sign as he had stated, this indicated he also made a misjudgment of V2's velocity and gap distance prior to proceeding into the intersection.
The critical pre-crash event for V2 was coded: other vehicle encroachment; from crossing street, across path. The critical reason was not coded to this vehicle.
